{\pard\s1\f1\fs32\b\cf2 SECTION 1 - PROGRAM OVERVIEW\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s2\f1\fs28\b 1.1  Purpose\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 This Cost Analysis Requirements Description (CARD) defines the scope, assumptions, boundaries, and data requirements for an Independent Cost Estimate (ICE) of the NASA Lunar Gateway program. The CARD is prepared in accordance with NASA Policy Requirement (NPR) 7120.5F, \i NASA Space Flight Program and Project Management Requirements\i0 , and NASA Cost Estimating Handbook (CEH) Version 4.0 (2015). This CARD satisfies the requirement for an ICE prior to the Gateway Program Commitment Agreement (PCA).\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 The ICE is to be performed by an independent cost estimating organization (herein, the Aerospace Corporation serving as the NASA Independent Cost Assessment Group, NICAG). The ICE will be used to validate the NASA program office estimate and inform the NASA Associate Administrator\rquote s approval of the Gateway PCA baseline.\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s2\f1\fs28\b 1.2  Program Background and Authorization\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 The Lunar Gateway (hereinafter \ldblquote Gateway\rdblquote ) is a NASA-led international space station to be placed in a Near-Rectilinear Halo Orbit (NRHO) around the Moon. Gateway serves as the staging platform for the Artemis program\rquote s sustained lunar exploration objectives. Authorization derives from:\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360\bullet\tab NASA Authorization Act of 2017 (Public Law 115-10), directing a cis-lunar station;\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360\bullet\tab Space Policy Directive 1 (December 2017), directing NASA to return humans to the Moon;\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360\bullet\tab Space Policy Directive 6 (December 2020), directing development of the Gateway;\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360\bullet\tab National Space Exploration Campaign Report (September 2018).\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 The Gateway Program Office (GPO) is located at NASA Johnson Space Center (JSC), Houston, Texas. Gateway is one of three major Artemis program elements, alongside the Space Launch System (SLS) and the Orion Multi-Purpose Crew Vehicle.\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s2\f1\fs28\b 1.3  International Partners\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 Gateway is the most internationally collaborative human spaceflight program since the International Space Station (ISS). The following agencies have signed Implementing Arrangements with NASA:\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360\bullet\tab {\b European Space Agency (ESA):} Providing the International Habitation Module (I-HAB) and ESPRIT Module (Lunar Link and Lunar View), valued at approximately \u8364?1.0 billion;\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360\bullet\tab {\b Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency (JAXA):} Providing the Environmental Control and Life Support System (ECLSS) for I-HAB, valued at approximately \u165?15 billion;\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360\bullet\tab {\b Canadian Space Agency (CSA):} Providing Canadarm3 robotic systems, the largest Canadian space investment in history at approximately CAD $2.05 billion;\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360\bullet\tab {\b Mohammed Bin Rashid Space Centre (MBRSC, UAE):} Providing the Lunar Airlock, announced January 2024;\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360\bullet\tab {\b Mohammed Bin Rashid Space Centre (MBRSC, UAE):} Contributing the first Arab astronaut mission to a lunar-vicinity space station.\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 Partner contributions are not directly included in the NASA program cost baseline but are reflected in this CARD for completeness. The NASA cost estimate covers only NASA-funded activities.\par}
\pard\par

\pard\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brdr0\par
{\pard\s1\f1\fs32\b\cf2 SECTION 2 - SYSTEM DESCRIPTION\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s2\f1\fs28\b 2.1  Gateway Orbital Environment\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 Gateway operates in a Near-Rectilinear Halo Orbit (NRHO), a member of the L2 Lyapunov/halo orbit family in the Earth-Moon three-body system. The selected NRHO has the following characteristics:\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720\f2 Orbital Period:    6.56 days\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Perilune Altitude: ~3,366 km (above lunar south pole region)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Apolune Altitude:  ~71,100 km\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Orbit Eccentricity: ~0.869\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Inclination (lunar): ~90 degrees (polar)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Station-keeping dV: ~10 m/s per year (PPE AEPS)\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 NRHO was selected for Gateway based on its near-stability (minimal station-keeping), continuous line-of-sight to Earth, access to the lunar south pole, and favorable geometry for HLS descent trajectories to the lunar surface. The orbit was confirmed by NASA\rquote s Advanced Exploration Systems (AES) program through extensive trajectory analysis.\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s2\f1\fs28\b 2.2  Gateway Modules and Elements\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 Gateway consists of the following elements, in order of launch:\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\s3\f1\fs24\b 2.2.1  Power and Propulsion Element (PPE)\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 The PPE is a solar electric propulsion (SEP) spacecraft built by Maxar Technologies under a $375 million firm-fixed-price contract. Key characteristics:\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Contractor:          Maxar Technologies (Westminster, CO)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Contract Type:       Firm-Fixed-Price (FFP)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Contract Value:      $375,000,000\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Solar Power:         ~60 kW Beginning-of-Life (BOL)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Propulsion:          Advanced Electric Propulsion System (AEPS)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720                      Hall-effect ion thrusters (4 x 12.5 kW)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Propellant:          Xenon (quantity TBD for mission life)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Design Life:         15 years minimum\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Launch:              NET April 2027 on SpaceX Falcon Heavy\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 The PPE will conduct a 12-month solo operations demonstration before HALO systems are activated, verifying propulsion performance in the lunar environment.\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s3\f1\fs24\b 2.2.2  Habitation and Logistics Outpost (HALO)\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 HALO is the first crewed pressurized module, providing initial habitation and logistics storage. Key characteristics:\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 System Contractor:    Northrop Grumman Innovation Systems (NGIS)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Structural Subcon.:   Thales Alenia Space (Turin, Italy)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Phase A/B Contract:   $187,000,000 (June 2020)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Fab/Integration Con.: $935,000,000 (July 2021)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Total HALO Cost:      $1,122,000,000\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Contractor Charges:   ~$100M taken by NG against contract (2023)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Habitable Volume:     ~125 cubic meters (pressurized)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Crew Capacity:        Up to 4 crew for short-duration visits\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Docking Ports:        5 IDS-compatible ports\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Launch:               Co-launched with PPE on Falcon Heavy 2027\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 HALO represents the critical path element for Gateway Initial Capability. Schedule risk is high given the existing contractor losses and mass margin concern identified by GAO.\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s3\f1\fs24\b 2.2.3  International Habitation Module (I-HAB)\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 I-HAB is an ESA-led habitation expansion module with JAXA ECLSS contribution:\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Lead Agency:      European Space Agency (ESA)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Prime Contractor: Thales Alenia Space (Turin/Rome, Italy)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 ECLSS Provider:   JAXA (Japan Aerospace Exploration Agency)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 ESA Contract:     ~\u8364?565M (approx. $620M USD)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Launch:           Co-manifested on SLS Block 1B, Artemis IV (NET Sept 2028)\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s3\f1\fs24\b 2.2.4  ESPRIT Module (European System Providing Refueling Infrastructure and Telecommunications)\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 ESPRIT consists of two elements delivered in two separate launches:\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Prime Contractor: Thales Alenia Space (France/Italy) + OHB\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 ESA Contract:     \u8364?296.5M initial + \u8364?164M amendment (Oct 2024)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720                   Total: \u8364?460.5M (~$505M USD)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Lunar Link:       External Ka-band comms; launched with HALO in 2027\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Lunar View:       Pressurized module with windows + xenon; NET 2029\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s3\f1\fs24\b 2.2.5  Lunar Airlock (UAE Contribution)\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 The Lunar Airlock is a Mohammed Bin Rashid Space Centre (UAE) contribution enabling EVA from Gateway:\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Lead Agency:      MBRSC (Mohammed Bin Rashid Space Centre, UAE)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Prime Contractor: Thales Alenia Space\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Announcement:     January 2024\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Estimated Cost:   $195M (NASA analog estimate; not NASA-funded)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Target Launch:    NET 2030 on Artemis VI or commercial vehicle\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s3\f1\fs24\b 2.2.6  Canadarm3\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Lead Agency:      Canadian Space Agency (CSA)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Prime Contractor: MDA Space (Brampton, Ontario)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Total Investment: CAD $2.05 billion (~USD $1.5B)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Elements:         17m Large Arm + small dexterous arm\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Capability:       AI-enabled autonomous maintenance and inspection\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Target Delivery:  Artemis V mission, NET December 2029\par}
\pard\par

