{\pard\s1\f1\fs32\b\cf2 SECTION 3 - COST ESTIMATE SCOPE AND ASSUMPTIONS\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s2\f1\fs28\b 3.1  Scope of Estimate\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 The ICE shall estimate all NASA-funded costs for the Lunar Gateway program from Fiscal Year (FY) 2020 through FY2033, encompassing the period from formal development start through the first two years of sustained crewed operations. The Gateway Work Breakdown Structure (WBS) is defined in gateway_wbs.csv (100 elements; three levels; NASA/SP-20210023927 compliant). Specifically, the ICE shall include:\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 (a) WBS 1.1 Program Management (7 Level 3 elements; FY2020-FY2033)\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 (b) WBS 1.2 Systems Engineering and Integration (8 Level 3 elements; includes mass properties 1.2.3 and V&V planning 1.2.8)\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 (c) WBS 1.3 Power and Propulsion Element (8 Level 3 elements; NASA oversight of Maxar FFP; Maxar contract value included in total)\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 (d) WBS 1.4 Habitation and Logistics Outpost (9 Level 3 elements; includes radiation shielding 1.4.9)\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 (e) WBS 1.5, 1.6, 1.7, 1.8 International Partner Elements (NASA oversight and integration costs only; partner development costs excluded per GR-07)\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 (f) WBS 1.9 Integration, Assembly, and Test (8 Level 3 elements; NGIS Gilbert AZ and KSC)\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 (g) WBS 1.10 Launch Services (6 Level 3 elements; Falcon Heavy FFP, SLS co-manifest integration, commercial launches)\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 (h) WBS 1.11 Ground Systems (6 Level 3 elements; MCC-H, DSN, FDF, cybersecurity 1.11.6)\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 (i) WBS 1.12 Mission Operations (8 Level 3 elements; through FY2033)\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 (j) Management Reserve and Unallocated Future Expenses (UFE) per WBS 1.0\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 {\b Not in scope} for the NASA ICE (covered by partner agencies independently):\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 \bullet\tab ESA ESPRIT and I-HAB development costs (ESA-funded, ESA-estimated)\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 \bullet\tab JAXA I-HAB ECLSS development costs\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 \bullet\tab CSA/MDA Canadarm3 development costs\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 \bullet\tab UAE Airlock development costs\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 \bullet\tab SLS vehicle and Orion program costs\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 \bullet\tab HLS (Starship) program costs\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 \bullet\tab Lunar surface systems\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s2\f1\fs28\b 3.2  Estimate Basis and Methodology\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 The Aerospace Corporation ICE shall employ the following methodologies, consistent with GAO Cost Estimating and Assessment Guide (2020) best practices:\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b Analogy:} For HALO module, analogize to Cygnus pressurized cargo module (Northrop Grumman heritage) adjusted for human-rating requirements, life support, and deep-space qualification. Apply complexity adjustment factors for cis-lunar vs. LEO environment (+30-50% per NASA Cost-Estimating Parametric Model for Spacecraft, CEPAMS).\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b Parametric:} Use NASA CEPAMS and the PRICE-H cost model for hardware elements. Apply relevant cost estimating relationships (CERs) from historical NASA spacecraft programs (ISS modules: Unity, Harmony, Tranquility; ATV; HTV).\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b Engineering Build-Up (EBU):} For mission operations, use staffing plan multiplied by government and contractor labor rates from NASA schedule databases. Use historical ISS operations cost per crewed mission day as the analog baseline.\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b Contractor Data:} Review Northrop Grumman and Maxar Technologies Contract Performance Reports (CPRs) submitted monthly under EVM requirements. HALO cost-at-completion (CAC) derived from CPR data adjusted for assessed realism.\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s2\f1\fs28\b 3.3  Cost Estimate Basis Ground Rules\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 The ICE shall adhere to the following ground rules:\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b GR-01:} All costs expressed in then-year (TY) dollars unless otherwise specified. FY2022 base year for constant-year analysis. Escalation applied per OMB Circular A-94 Table C inflation indices.\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b GR-02:} Full cost accounting per NASA Full Cost Policy; includes civil servant labor at applicable JSC blended rates (estimated $285,000/FTE-year FY2022), overhead, and G&A.\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b GR-03:} No reserve included in ICE point estimate; ICE S-curve to show 50th and 70th percentile cost risk ranges.\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b GR-04:} Launch vehicle costs include only the $331.8M SpaceX Falcon Heavy contract value for PPE/HALO. No escalation applied to FFP contract value.\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b GR-05:} PPE FFP contract value ($375M) included as-is; ICE provides independent assessment of whether the FFP price is reasonable, not a re-estimate.\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b GR-06:} Cost phasing based on NASA-provided IMS; if IMS is considered unrealistic, ICE team may adjust phasing with rationale.\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b GR-07:} Government Furnished Equipment (GFE) costs included where NASA-provided; international partner GFE excluded.\par}
\pard\par

\pard\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brdr0\par
{\pard\s1\f1\fs32\b\cf2 SECTION 4 - TECHNICAL ASSUMPTIONS\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s2\f1\fs28\b 4.1  System-Level Technical Assumptions\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b TA-01:} PPE achieves 60 kW beginning-of-life (BOL) solar power generation, degrading to ~45 kW end-of-life (EOL) at 15 years. AEPS thrusters achieve 12.5 kW each at nominal operating power.\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b TA-02:} PPE/HALO combined launch mass does not exceed Falcon Heavy Block 5 Expendable mass-to-C3 capability. Mass margin positive at time of ICE. {\b NOTE: This assumption is flagged as high risk per GAO-24-106878 (July 2024); mass margin is currently near-zero and may be negative.}\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b TA-03:} NRHO station-keeping delta-V budget is 10 m/s per year; PPE carries sufficient xenon for 15-year mission life plus 25% margin.\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b TA-04:} HALO ECLSS meets NASA-STD-3001 requirements for crew habitation for mission durations of up to 30 days per crewed visit.\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b TA-05:} Gateway is designed for a nominal uncrewed duration of 200 days between crewed visits, with autonomous fault management covering all critical systems.\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b TA-06:} I-HAB launches co-manifested on SLS Block 1B as the secondary payload with Orion on Artemis IV. SLS Block 1B performance to TLI is assumed sufficient for the Orion + I-HAB mass.\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b TA-07:} Canadarm3 achieves TRL 6 for autonomous inspection at CDR; full AI autonomy achieved by first crewed Canadarm3 operation (Artemis V, 2029).\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b TA-08:} Xenon on-orbit transfer from ESPRIT Lunar View to PPE achieves TRL 6 prior to ESPRIT launch; first transfer demonstration completed within 90 days of Lunar View docking.\par}
\pard\par

