{\pard\s2\f1\fs28\b 5.2  Schedule Risk Factors\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b SR-01:} {\b Mass Margin Impact on Schedule (Risk R-001, score 20).} GAO-24-106878 found that PPE and HALO must launch at least 12 months before Artemis IV (M-029, October 2028) to allow adequate checkout time. Current committed launch date is April 2027 (M-024, T-132), providing approximately 18 months of margin. Mass reduction rework per T-009 tiger team is on critical path; delays to T-009 actions can compress T-121 through T-131 environmental test and launch campaign window.\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b SR-02:} {\b SLS Block 1B / EUS Readiness (Risk R-013, score 10).} The I-HAB co-manifested launch (M-029, T-139) is dependent on SLS Block 1B with the Exploration Upper Stage (EUS). EUS development carries schedule risk (R-013). Any slip to Artemis IV availability affects I-HAB delivery and first crewed Gateway milestone M-030.\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b SR-03:} {\b HALO ECLSS Qualification.} HALO ECLSS qualification testing has been identified as a potential late schedule driver. ISS ECLSS qualification took 4 years; HALO schedule allocates 3 years. ICE shall assess realism.\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b SR-04:} {\b Environmental Test Anomaly.} One anomaly during acoustic or thermal vacuum testing requiring hardware replacement or redesign could add 6-12 months to schedule.\par}
\pard\par

\pard\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brdr0\par
{\pard\s1\f1\fs32\b\cf2 SECTION 6 - DEVELOPMENT APPROACH\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s2\f1\fs28\b 6.1  Acquisition Strategy\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 Gateway employs a mixed acquisition strategy reflecting the program\rquote s unique international character and commercial opportunity:\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b PPE:} Firm-Fixed-Price (FFP) contract with Maxar Technologies. The FFP structure was used to incentivize commercial innovation and leverage Maxar\rquote s commercial satellite bus heritage. Price risk is borne by the contractor.\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b HALO:} Cost-reimbursable for Phase A/B ($187M) transitioning to Firm-Fixed-Price for fabrication and integration ($935M). The FFP approach on HALO has resulted in approximately $100M in contractor losses (2023) due to scope growth and design changes driven by evolving NASA requirements. The ICE shall assess whether the current contract structure is executable at the committed price.\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b Launch Services:} FFP commercial contract with SpaceX for Falcon Heavy. This represents the lowest-risk contract type for a well-defined launch service.\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b Systems Engineering and Mission Operations:} Cost-Plus-Fixed-Fee (CPFF) support service contracts with NASA JSC civil servants as technical leads. Contractors provide engineering support under omnibus contracts (e.g., JETS, ODIN).\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s2\f1\fs28\b 6.2  Heritage and New Development Balance\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 The table below summarizes heritage vs. new development for major Gateway elements:\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Element    Heritage Basis                  New Dev Fraction\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 ---------------------------------------------------------------\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 PPE        Maxar commercial satellite bus    ~40% new (AEPS, ROSA)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 HALO       Cygnus cargo module (TAS)         ~60% new (ECLSS, avionics)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 I-HAB      ATV/Columbus heritage (TAS)       ~55% new (deep-space life support)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 ESPRIT     No direct heritage                ~75% new\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Airlock    Quest ISS Airlock (analog)        ~65% new\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Canadarm3  Canadarm2/SSRMS (MDA)             ~50% new (AI, longer reach)\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 Higher new development fractions are associated with greater cost and schedule risk. The ICE shall apply appropriate cost risk multipliers based on heritage fraction and TRL of key subsystems at time of contract award.\par}
\pard\par

\pard\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brdr0\par
{\pard\s1\f1\fs32\b\cf2 SECTION 7 - PRODUCTION ASSUMPTIONS\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s2\f1\fs28\b 7.1  Production Quantity\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 Gateway is a one-of-a-kind development (quantity = 1 per module type). There is no planned production run for any Gateway module. The ICE shall therefore apply no learning curve benefits to hardware cost estimates. Any repetitive elements (e.g., docking adapters, solar array panels) shall use appropriate repetition factors at the component level only.\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s2\f1\fs28\b 7.2  Long-Lead Items\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 The following items are designated long-lead and must be procured early to avoid schedule risk:\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 (a) Xenon propellant (100+ kg lot); global supply constraint; early Air Products and Chemicals procurement;\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 (b) AEPS Hall-effect thrusters (Aerojet Rocketdyne); 36-month lead time from order to delivery;\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 (c) Advanced solar array flexible blanket materials (MMA Design/MDA);\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 (d) Space-grade microprocessors and FPGAs (radiation-hardened); subject to export controls and limited suppliers;\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 (e) High-pressure composite overwrapped pressure vessels (COPVs) for xenon tanks.\par}
\pard\par

\pard\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brdr0\par
{\pard\s1\f1\fs32\b\cf2 SECTION 8 - OPERATIONS ASSUMPTIONS\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s2\f1\fs28\b 8.1  Operational Phases\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 Gateway operations are divided into three phases:\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b Phase 1 - Uncrewed Operations (2027-2028):} Following PPE/HALO launch, Gateway operates autonomously in NRHO for approximately 9-10 months during the low-thrust transit and initial checkout. Staffing: reduced ground team (~25 flight controllers for critical events, 8 for nominal monitoring).\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b Phase 2 - Initial Crewed Operations (2028-2031):} Artemis IV through Artemis VI; crewed visits of 30-90 days. Staffing: ~300 personnel for peak crewed operations (flight directors, controllers, MOD support). Uncrewed periods between missions: reduced to 50 personnel.\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b Phase 3 - Sustained Operations (2031+):} Full Gateway IOC with all modules; sustained mission tempo of 2 crewed missions per year. Staffing optimized based on operational experience.\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s2\f1\fs28\b 8.2  Analog: ISS Operations Cost Basis\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 ISS annual operations cost is approximately $3.0-4.0 billion (FY2022 dollars) for a 12-person-year crew complement. Gateway operates at ~1/10th the scale of ISS (4 crew per visit, 2-3 visits per year, each 30-90 days). Applying a 10% ISS operations cost proxy suggests annual Gateway operations cost of $300-400M at steady-state. This is consistent with the NASA FY2025 budget request structure and the $788M FY2026-FY2033 operations estimate in the program plan.\par}
\pard\par

\pard\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brdr0\par
{\pard\s1\f1\fs32\b\cf2 SECTION 9 - COST RISK ASSESSMENT\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s2\f1\fs28\b 9.1  Risk-Adjusted Cost Estimate Requirement\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 The ICE shall include a Monte Carlo cost risk simulation (minimum 10,000 iterations) producing an S-curve showing probability of not exceeding estimated costs. The ICE shall present the following confidence levels:\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 Confidence Level    Estimated Cost (TBD by ICE team)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 50th Percentile     (Point Estimate)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 70th Percentile     (NASA planning standard for reserves)\par}
{\pard\f2\fs20\li720 80th Percentile     (High confidence bound)\par}
\pard\par

{\pard\s2\f1\fs28\b 9.2  Key Cost Risk Drivers\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24 Based on program status and GAO-24-106878, the following are assessed as primary cost risk drivers ranked by expected cost impact:\par}
\pard\par
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b Rank 1 - HALO Mass Reduction Rework:} Mass reduction to meet Falcon Heavy performance requires design changes and re-qualification testing; estimated range of additional cost $50M-$300M;\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b Rank 2 - HALO ECLSS Performance Rework:} ECLSS performance shortfalls may require additional development and test iterations; estimated additional cost $30M-$180M;\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b Rank 3 - Mission Operations Scope Growth:} Operational complexity exceeding baseline may require additional staffing; range $50M-$200M;\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b Rank 4 - PPE Propulsion System Anomaly:} AEPS thruster failure during solo demo requiring redesign; range $20M-$150M;\par}
{\pard\f0\fs24\li360 {\b Rank 5 - Launch Delay / Additional Falcon Heavy Mission:} If mass cannot be reduced, dedicated second launch for deferred hardware; range $250M-$450M additional.\par}
\pard\par

\pard\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brdr0\par
